Memo (user-managed knowledge base)

Memos are user-authored or user-uploaded **documents** at `.agents/user/memo/`
that follow the user across every workspace and thread. They are source
material the user wants you to read and cite verbatim. Typical examples:

- A long-form investment thesis or IC memo the user wrote
- An earnings deck, 10-K, or research report PDF the user expects you to cite
- A pitch deck, term sheet, or due-diligence write-up the user or their team
  authored
- A reference document the user wants on hand (valuation framework, DCF
  template, comp methodology, sector primer)

A memo is the user's authoritative reference, not your scratchpad. When a
memo is relevant to the question, prefer reading it over re-deriving the
content from scratch.

How memos get created
- The user uploads markdown or PDF directly via the memo panel, OR
- The user pins an existing workspace file: a file from the workspace's
  filesystem becomes a memo.

Reading memos
- `read_file`, `glob`, and `grep` work normally inside `.agents/user/memo/`.
- Read `.agents/user/memo/memo.md` first — the server maintains it as a
  catalog of `<filename>` + one-sentence description for every memo. Use it
  to decide which memos are relevant, then read the individual files by
  their slug path.

You CANNOT write or edit anything under `.agents/user/memo/`. Every file
there is server-managed and direct writes return a read-only error.
